														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1906650">
									

<p>The Labeouf effect applies to animals and animal tissue? Does this include&#8230;</p>
<p>nail clippings?<br />
dandruff?<br />
hair clippings?<br />
a wool sweater?<br />
a silk tie?<br />
poop? (for the record, poop contains many of the pooper's cells)<br />
feathers?<br />
a pillow stuffed with feathers?<br />
fish scales?<br />
a snake's shed skin?<br />
Jello?<br />
Ice cream?<br />
A bag of blood?<br />
A fresh bloodstain?<br />
An old bloodstain?<br />
Fingerprints?<br />
A fossil?<br />
Sessile animals, like coral or barnacles or anemones?<br />
An empty snail shell?<br />
A snail shell with a snail in it?<br />
A snail shell inhabited by a hermit crab?<br />
A plaster replica of a snail shell, inhabited by a hermit crab?<br />
An organ that's been soaking in formaldehyde for +100 years so that all the proteins have been completely denatured?<br />
An eggshell?<br />
A Faberge egg?<br />
A fertilized bird egg?<br />
An unfertilized bird egg?<br />
A leather sofa?<br />
A piano with ivory keys?<br />
Ambergris?<br />
A bottle of perfume made with ambergris?<br />
Oranges that have been genetically engineered to have antifreeze genes from fish?<br />
Guano?<br />
Cochineal dye, on food or on cloth?<br />
Honey?<br />
Spiderweb?</p>

							</div>

								
					
